</p><textarea readonly="" accesskey="," id="wpTextbox1" cols="80" rows="25" style="" lang="en" dir="ltr" name="wpTextbox1">== User Requirements==

* The user accesses the mobile device through the Appliance Control Unit (ACU) mode of the wheelchair where the input for the mobile device can be set with at least a single binary switch and at most four binary switches.
* User has the ability to access at least the basic features of a mobile device (e.g.: phone service, location based services, mp3 player, text messaging).
* The system shall be extensible to other capabilities for accessibility beyond wheelchair use and basic mobile device services, to further improve quality of life for wheelchair users (e.g.: accessibility to home environmental control unit).

==The Problem Space==

Enabling access to mobile devices through a powered-wheelchair is a complex task. Specially since mobile device designers do not typically pay attention to the experience of powered wheelchair users when developing their products. On the other hand, the connectivity and convenience of mobile devices (in particular smart phones) offer unique opportunities for simplifying access to precious digital and even physical resources by powered wheelchair users.

Rather than focusing on independent access goals (e.g., text input). The Tekla project will approach the problem of access to mobile devices as a comprehensive experience of access in daily life, with an initial emphasis on the experience of powered-wheelchair users.

===Processing Input from the Wheelchair===

Standard appliance control units (ACU) provide powered wheelchair users with four simple binary (i.e., ON/OFF) switches. These switches are equivalent to the four directions (i.e., FWD, BACK, LEFT, RIGHT) that users would normally employ to drive the wheelchair. Depending on a variety of circumstances some users, may only have access to a single binary switch to access external appliances such as a smart phone. Thus, the input scheme used should be flexible enough to allow access with anywhere between 1 to 4 binary switches.

====Gesture Manager====

One alternative way to increase the number of inputs from the wheelchair would be to allow users to define "switch gestures" that they can reliably reproduce. In addition to a normal switch press, a switch gesture would consist of a timed activation or sequence such as a ''double'' or ''long'' press.

====Bluetooth Interface====

In order to transfer the commands from the wheelchair to the mobile device under control, a driver interface must be used. This interface must be able to read the state of up to 4 binary switch inputs from the wheelchair's ACU, and relay this information to the client device under control. In principle, both wired or wireless connections may be used to facilitate data transfer between the powered wheelchair and client devices, however, it is important to note that in order to allow for the exchange of data with target devices, wired connections require the availability of physical adaptors compatible with each target device and capable of supporting standard connectors and protocols. Unfortunately, although the use of standard connectors and protocols for wired connections to mobile devices has increased, many continue to be proprietary and thus, cannot be adapted. In contrast, wireless interfaces based on Local Area Network technologies (e.g., Bluetooth and WiFi) are more consistently implemented across mobile devices. In particular, Bluetooth offers the serial port profile or SPP, which can be used to establish a serial bidirectional communication channel between paired Bluetooth devices. Moreover, dedicated Bluetooth modules such as the [http://www.arduino.cc/en/Guide/ArduinoBT Arduino BT board] are available at a fraction of the cost of WiFi peripherals. Thus, Bluetooth is a natural choice for implementing bi-directional communication between powered wheelchair and mobile devices.

====Other Ideas====
* Phillip Quiza: Add the wheelchair as a custom input device hooked up to the Gestures/Motion APIs on Android

===Accessibility Manager vs. Dedicated User Interface===
From the users' perspective, there are at least two ways to think about the problem of accessing a smart phone from a powered wheelchair:

====A11y Manager====
The A11y Manager is a background application that would allow users to interact directly with the active elements or interface widgets on the phone's screen. This typically requires the elements of the graphical user interface (GUI) to define a ''focus'' state or event and to expose themselves to the manager application running in the background. In desktops, this set of features has come to be known as keyboard accessibility because they make it possible for an interface to be entirely controlled with a keyboard. A desktop examples of a library that enables this functionality is [http://projects.gnome.org/accessibility/ AT-SPI] on Linux.

{|
|-
! Advantages
! Disadvantages
|-
|
* Scalable: If properly implemented, will not require new applications to be adapted
* Transparent: Users don't have to learn a separate interface
|
* Most effective with a full-keyboard (but we only have 4 switches!)
* Switch access requires implementation of in-place scanning for the operating system's (OS) GUI
* Depends on the state and implementation of accessibility in the OS
|}

====Dedicated UI====
This access modality describes the use of a proxy application that defines a catalogue of a subset of the potential actions or commands that can be triggered on the device and makes such catalogue available to the user through a custom interface (e.g., a multi-level, scanning linear menu). This Dedicated UI is intended to substitute the usual mode of interaction with the device. An example is the [http://code.google.com/p/eyes-free/ eyes-free shell] on Android.

{|
|-
! Advantages
! Disadvantages
|-
|
* Does not depend on the state and implementation of accessibility in the OS
* Easy to get started: basic functionality can be quickly enabled
* Interface can be fully adapted
|
* Not scalable: new applications will likely require tweaking/adaptation
* Not transparent: users must adapt to a separate interface (although this interface may be made more intuitive than the original one available in the OS)
|}

===Text Input===
====Scanning OSK====
Scanning on-screen keyboards (OSK) are a standard method of enabling switch-based text input. These keyboards present a character set on the screen arranged in rows and columns. When 3 or more switches are available, they can be used directly to navigate the character matrix, however, if only one or two switches are available, the use of [[media:Osk-wireframe.gif|scanning]]&lt;ref name="switch_guide">[http://www.ace-centre.org.uk/assets/Product%20Downloads/SwitchScanningMaster_8_472.pdf "Switch Access, A Comprehensive Guide"]&lt;/ref> becomes essential. OSKs are in general a very slow method for text input, specially if additional aids such as word prediction are unavailable. An animation demonstrating the functionality of a self-scanning OSK with a touch-screen as a single input switch is available here: http://wiki.scyp.atrc.utoronto.ca/w/File:Osk-wireframe.gif. Note that since the entire screen is used as a switch, the user does not have to target particular keys.

====Morse Code?====
An alternative to self-scanning on-screen keyboards (OSK) is the use of serial communication protocols such as Morse code. These are not very popular in North America but have some acceptance in Asia&lt;ref>Luo CH, Shih CH: Adaptive Morse-coded single-switch communication system for the disabled. International Journal of Bio-Medical Computing 1996, 41(2):99-106. [http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/0020-7101(96)01163-4 Publisher Full Text]&lt;/ref>
,&lt;ref>Yang C, Chuang L, Yang C, Luo C: Internet access for disabled persons using morse code. International journal of computers &amp; applications 2004, 26:10-6.&lt;/ref>. Serial communication protocols may be faster than self-scanning OSKs and do not require visual feedback, however, the user must learn the appropriate switch activation sequences to create each one of the characters he/she wishes to type.

===Element Browsing===
[[File:menu.png|300px|thumb|right|A sample scheme for switch-based menu navigation]]
Regardless of whether the solution is an a11y manager sitting in the background or a dedicated UI, a proper browsing strategy must be developed.

The figure on the right shows a 4-switch scheme for browsing multi-level menus. If only 3 switches are available, the virtual menu can alternatively include a "Back/Cancel" item. For two switches, only clockwise or counter-clockwise navigation may be enabled. Finally, with only one switch, self- or user-scanning can do the trick.&lt;ref name="switch_guide" />

